# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: meltano
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Since a Meltano project is just a directory on your filesystem containing text-based files, you can treat it like any other software development project and benefit from DataOps best practices such as version control, code review, and continuous integration and deployment (CI/CD).
[src:meltano/concepts-project] You can initialize a new Meltano project using `meltano init`.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] At a minimum, a Meltano project must contain a project file named `meltano.yml`, which contains your project configuration and tells Meltano that a particular directory is a Meltano project.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] The only required property is `version`, which currently always holds the value `1`.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] You can find a formal JSON Schema for the specification on SchemaStore.org or directly in the main repository here, which can be useful for code generation by many tools like datamodel-code-generator or swagger-codegen.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] You can customize the YAML formatting of this file (indentation, spacing, etc.) using Meltano's user YAML configuration.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] At the root of `meltano.yml`, and usually at the top of the file, you will find project-specific configuration.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] In a newly initialized project, a few environments will be populated to get you started.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] To learn which settings are available, refer to the Settings reference.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Your project's plugins, typically added to your project using `meltano add`, are defined under the `plugins` property, inside an array named after the plugin type (e.g.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] 3. configuration that can be defined across various layers, including the definition's `config` property.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] When a plugin is added using `meltano add`, the `pip_url` is automatically repeated in the plugin definition for convenience.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] In order to support version-specific pip constraint files, the pip_url value can optionally be parameterized using the `${MELTANO__PYTHON_VERSION}` variable.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] This is a special variable populated by Meltano with the specific version of Python used to install the plugin and will inject the major and minor versions (e.g.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] A plugin defined with an `inherit_from` property inherits its base plugin description from another plugin identified by name.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] To learn how to add an inheriting plugin to your project, refer to the Plugin Management guide.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] To learn how to add a custom plugin to your project, refer to the Plugin Management guide.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] To learn how to add a discoverable plugin to your project, refer to the Plugin Management guide.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] If no `variant` is specified, the *original* variant supported by Meltano is used.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Note that this is not necessarily the *default* variant that is recommended to new users and would be used if the plugin were newly added to the project.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] A plugin's configuration is stored under a `config` property.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Plugin commands are defined by the `commands` property.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] The keys are the name of the command and the values are the arguments to be passed to the plugin executable.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] These can contain dynamic references to configuration using the Environment variable form of the configuration option.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Commands can optionally specify some documentation displayed when listing commands.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] They can also optionally specify an alternative executable from the default one for the plugin.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Commands can specify a `container_spec` for containerized execution.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] To execute containerized commands where possible, use the `--containers` flag.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] See the full YAML reference for the container spec for more information.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Your project's predefined pipelines, typically created using `meltano job`, are defined under the `jobs` property.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] You can learn more about how tasks are defined and run in the `meltano job` documentation.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Your project's pipeline schedules, typically created using `meltano schedule`, are defined under the `schedules` property.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] The value for `job` must be the name of an existing job within the project.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] To learn more about pipeline schedules and orchestration, refer to the Orchestration guide.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] As your project grows, and your `meltano.yml` with it, you may wish to break your config into multiple `.yml` files and to store those subfiles in various places in your Project folder hierarchy.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Meltano will use these paths or patterns to collect the config from them for use in your Project.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Although the creation of subfiles is manual, once created any elements within each subfile can be updated using the `meltano config` CLI.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Adding new config elements places them in `meltano.yml`.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] We are working on ways to direct new config into specific subfiles (#2985).
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Currently supported elements in subfiles are plugins, schedules and environments.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] To better integrate with software other than the core Meltano library and CLI, `meltano.yml` support "annotations", which is a dictionary that map from tool/vendor names to arbitrary dictionaries with whatever that tool/vendor wants to annotate the Meltano config with.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] The core Meltano library and CLI never access the `annotations` field.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] To access it, one must read `meltano.yml`.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Nothing within an `annotations` field should be thought of as part of Meltano's own configuration - it is merely extra data that Meltano permits within its configuration files.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] A newly initialized project comes with a `.gitignore` file to ensure that environment-specific and potentially sensitive configuration stored inside the `.meltano` directory and `.env` file is not leaked accidentally.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] All other files are recommended to be checked into the repository and shared between all users and environments that may use the project.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Optionally, your project can contain a `.env` file specifying environment variables used to configure Meltano and its plugins.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Typically, this file is used to store configuration that is environment-specific or sensitive, and should not be stored in `meltano.yml` and checked into version control.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] `meltano config set <plugin>` will automatically store configuration in `meltano.yml` or `.env` as appropriate.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] In a newly initialized project, this file will be included in `.gitignore` by default.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Meltano stores various files for internal use inside a `.meltano` directory inside your project.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] These files are specific to the environment Meltano is running in, and should not be checked into version control.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] In a newly initialized project, this directory will be included in `.gitignore` by default.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] If `$MELTANO_SYS_DIR_ROOT` is set, all the above mentioned paths `.meltano/*` will point to `$MELTANO_SYS_DIR_ROOT/*`.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Meltano stores various types of metadata in a project-specific system database, that takes the shape of a `meltano.db` SQLite database stored inside the `.meltano` directory by default.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Other database backends are supported as well.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] Like all files stored in the `.meltano` directory, the system database is also environment-specific.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] You can choose to use a different system database backend or configuration using the `database_uri` setting.
[src:meltano/concepts-project] While you would usually not want to modify the system database directly, knowing what's in there can aid in debugging.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The decision to integrate data tends to arise when the volume, complexity (that is, big data) and need to share existing data explodes.
[src:meltano/data-integration] It has become the focus of extensive theoretical work, and numerous open problems remain unsolved.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Data integration encourages collaboration between internal as well as external users.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The data being integrated must be received from a heterogeneous database system and transformed to a single coherent data store that provides synchronous data across a network of files for clients.
[src:meltano/data-integration] A common use of data integration is in data mining when analyzing and extracting information from existing databases that can be useful for Business information.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Issues with combining heterogeneous data sources, often referred to as information silos, under a single query interface have existed for some time.
[src:meltano/data-integration] In the early 1980s, computer scientists began designing systems for interoperability of heterogeneous databases.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The first data integration system driven by structured metadata was designed in 1991 at the University of Minnesota for the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:meltano/data-integration] IPUMS used a data warehousing approach, which extracts, transforms, and loads data from heterogeneous sources into a unique view schema so data from different sources become compatible.
[src:meltano/data-integration] By making thousands of population databases interoperable, IPUMS demonstrated the feasibility of large-scale data integration.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The data warehouse approach offers a tightly coupled architecture because the data are already physically reconciled in a single queryable repository, so it usually takes little time to resolve queries.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The data warehouse approach is less feasible for data sets that are frequently updated, requiring the extract, transform, load (ETL) process to be continuously re-executed for synchronization.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Difficulties also arise in constructing data warehouses when one has only a query interface to summary data sources and no access to the full data.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This problem frequently emerges when integrating several commercial query services like travel or classified advertisement web applications.
[src:meltano/data-integration] A trend began in 2009 favoring the loose coupling of data and providing a unified query-interface to access real time data over a mediated schema (see Figure 2), which allows information to be retrieved directly from original databases.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This is consistent with the SOA approach popular in that era.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This approach relies on mappings between the mediated schema and the schema of original sources, and translating a query into decomposed queries to match the schema of the original databases.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Such mappings can be specified in two ways: as a mapping from entities in the mediated schema to entities in the original sources (the "Global-as-View" (GAV) approach), or as a mapping from entities in the original sources to the mediated schema (the "Local-as-View" (LAV) approach).
[src:meltano/data-integration] The latter approach requires more sophisticated inferences to resolve a query on the mediated schema, but makes it easier to add new data sources to a (stable) mediated schema.
[src:meltano/data-integration] As of 2010, some of the work in data integration research concerns the semantic integration problem.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This problem addresses not the structuring of the architecture of the integration, but how to resolve semantic conflicts between heterogeneous data sources.
[src:meltano/data-integration] For example, if two companies merge their databases, certain concepts and definitions in their respective schemas like "earnings" inevitably have different meanings.
[src:meltano/data-integration] In one database it may mean profits in dollars (a floating-point number), while in the other it might represent the number of sales (an integer).
[src:meltano/data-integration] A common strategy for the resolution of such problems involves the use of ontologies which explicitly define schema terms and thus help to resolve semantic conflicts.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This approach represents ontology-based data integration.
[src:meltano/data-integration] On the other hand, the problem of combining research results from different bioinformatics repositories requires bench-marking of the similarities, computed from different data sources, on a single criterion such as positive predictive value.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This enables the data sources to be directly comparable and can be integrated even when the natures of experiments are distinct.
[src:meltano/data-integration] As of 2011, it was determined that current data modeling methods were imparting data isolation into every data architecture in the form of islands of disparate data and information silos.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This data isolation is an unintended artifact of the data modeling methodology that results in the development of disparate data models.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Disparate data models, when instantiated as databases, form disparate databases.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Enhanced data model methodologies have been developed to eliminate the data isolation artifact and to promote the development of integrated data models.
[src:meltano/data-integration] One enhanced data modeling method recasts data models by augmenting them with structural metadata in the form of standardized data entities.
[src:meltano/data-integration] As a result of recasting multiple data models, the set of recast data models will now share one or more commonality relationships that relate the structural metadata now common to these data models.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Commonality relationships are a peer-to-peer type of entity relationships that relate the standardized data entities of multiple data models.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Multiple data models that contain the same standard data entity may participate in the same commonality relationship.
[src:meltano/data-integration] When integrated data models are instantiated as databases and are properly populated from a common set of master data, then these databases are integrated.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Since 2011, data hub approaches have been of greater interest than fully structured (typically relational) Enterprise Data Warehouses.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Since 2013, data lake approaches have risen to the level of Data Hubs.
[src:meltano/data-integration] (See all three search terms popularity on Google Trends.) These approaches combine unstructured or varied data into one location, but do not necessarily require an (often complex) master relational schema to structure and define all data in the Hub.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Data integration plays a big role in business regarding data collection used for studying the market.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Converting the raw data retrieved from consumers into coherent data is something businesses try to do when considering what steps they should take next.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Organizations are more frequently using data mining for collecting information and patterns from their databases, and this process helps them develop new business strategies to increase business performance and perform economic analyses more efficiently.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Compiling the large amount of data they collect to be stored in their system is a form of data integration adapted for Business intelligence to improve their chances of success.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Consider a web application where a user can query a variety of information about cities (such as crime statistics, weather, hotels, demographics, etc.).
[src:meltano/data-integration] Traditionally, the information must be stored in a single database with a single schema.
[src:meltano/data-integration] But any single enterprise would find information of this breadth somewhat difficult and expensive to collect.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Even if the resources exist to gather the data, it would likely duplicate data in existing crime databases, weather websites, and census data.
[src:meltano/data-integration] A data-integration solution may address this problem by considering these external resources as materialized views over a virtual mediated schema, resulting in "virtual data integration".
[src:meltano/data-integration] This means application-developers construct a virtual schema—the *mediated schema*—to best model the kinds of answers their users want.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Next, they design "wrappers" or adapters for each data source, such as the crime database and weather website.
[src:meltano/data-integration] These adapters simply transform the local query results (those returned by the respective websites or databases) into an easily processed form for the data integration solution (see figure 2).
[src:meltano/data-integration] When an application-user queries the mediated schema, the data-integration solution transforms this query into appropriate queries over the respective data sources.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Finally, the virtual database combines the results of these queries into the answer to the user's query.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This solution offers the convenience of adding new sources by simply constructing an adapter or an application software blade for them.
[src:meltano/data-integration] It contrasts with ETL systems or with a single database solution, which require manual integration of entire new data set into the system.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The virtual ETL solutions leverage virtual mediated schema to implement data harmonization; whereby the data are copied from the designated "master" source to the defined targets, field by field.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Advanced data virtualization is also built on the concept of object-oriented modeling in order to construct virtual mediated schema or virtual metadata repository, using hub and spoke architecture.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Each data source is disparate and as such is not designed to support reliable joins between data sources.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Therefore, data virtualization as well as data federation depends upon accidental data commonality to support combining data and information from disparate data sets.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Because of the lack of data value commonality across data sources, the return set may be inaccurate, incomplete, and impossible to validate.
[src:meltano/data-integration] One solution is to recast disparate databases to integrate these databases without the need for ETL.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The recast databases support commonality constraints where referential integrity may be enforced between databases.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The recast databases provide designed data access paths with data value commonality across databases.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The theory of data integration forms a subset of database theory and formalizes the underlying concepts of the problem in first-order logic.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Applying the theories gives indications as to the feasibility and difficulty of data integration.
[src:meltano/data-integration] While its definitions may appear abstract, they have sufficient generality to accommodate all manner of integration systems, including those that include nested relational / XML databases and those that treat databases as programs.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Connections to particular databases systems such as Oracle or DB2 are provided by implementation-level technologies such as JDBC and are not studied at the theoretical level.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Data integration systems are formally defined as a tuple $\left\langle G,S,M\right\rangle$ where G is the global (or mediated) schema, S is the heterogeneous set of source schemas, and M is the mapping that maps queries between the source and the global schemas.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Both G and S are expressed in languages over alphabets composed of symbols for each of their respective relations.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The mapping M consists of assertions between queries over G and queries over S .
[src:meltano/data-integration] When users pose queries over the data integration system, they pose queries over G and the mapping then asserts connections between the elements in the global schema and the source schemas.
[src:meltano/data-integration] A database over a schema is defined as a set of sets, one for each relation (in a relational database).
[src:meltano/data-integration] The database corresponding to the source schema S would comprise the set of sets of tuples for each of the heterogeneous data sources and is called the *source database*.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Note that this single source database may actually represent a collection of disconnected databases.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The database corresponding to the virtual mediated schema G is called the *global database*.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The global database must satisfy the mapping M with respect to the source database.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The legality of this mapping depends on the nature of the correspondence between G and S .
[src:meltano/data-integration] Two popular ways to model this correspondence exist: *Global as View* or GAV and *Local as View* or LAV.
[src:meltano/data-integration] GAV systems model the global database as a set of views over S .
[src:meltano/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of G a query over S .
[src:meltano/data-integration] Query processing becomes a straightforward operation due to the well-defined associations between G and S .
[src:meltano/data-integration] The burden of complexity falls on implementing mediator code instructing the data integration system exactly how to retrieve elements from the source databases.
[src:meltano/data-integration] If any new sources join the system, considerable effort may be necessary to update the mediator, thus the GAV approach appears preferable when the sources seem unlikely to change.
[src:meltano/data-integration] In a GAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer would first develop mediators for each of the city information sources and then design the global schema around these mediators.
[src:meltano/data-integration] For example, consider if one of the sources served a weather website.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The designer would likely then add a corresponding element for weather to the global schema.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Then the bulk of effort concentrates on writing the proper mediator code that will transform predicates on weather into a query over the weather website.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This effort can become complex if some other source also relates to weather, because the designer may need to write code to properly combine the results from the two sources.
[src:meltano/data-integration] On the other hand, in LAV, the source database is modeled as a set of views over G .
[src:meltano/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of S a query over G .
[src:meltano/data-integration] Here the exact associations between G and S are no longer well-defined.
[src:meltano/data-integration] As is illustrated in the next section, the burden of determining how to retrieve elements from the sources is placed on the query processor.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The benefit of an LAV modeling is that new sources can be added with far less work than in a GAV system, thus the LAV approach should be favored in cases where the mediated schema is less stable or likely to change.
[src:meltano/data-integration] In an LAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer designs the global schema first and then simply inputs the schemas of the respective city information sources.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Consider again if one of the sources serves a weather website.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The designer would add corresponding elements for weather to the global schema only if none existed already.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Then programmers write an adapter or wrapper for the website and add a schema description of the website's results to the source schemas.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The complexity of adding the new source moves from the designer to the query processor.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The theory of query processing in data integration systems is commonly expressed using conjunctive queries and Datalog, a purely declarative logic programming language.
[src:meltano/data-integration] One can loosely think of a conjunctive query as a logical function applied to the relations of a database such as " $f(A,B)$ where $A<B$ ".
[src:meltano/data-integration] If a tuple or set of tuples is substituted into the rule and satisfies it (makes it true), then we consider that tuple as part of the set of answers in the query.
[src:meltano/data-integration] While formal languages like Datalog express these queries concisely and without ambiguity, common SQL queries count as conjunctive queries as well.
[src:meltano/data-integration] In terms of data integration, "query containment" represents an important property of conjunctive queries.
[src:meltano/data-integration] A query A contains another query B (denoted $A\supset B$ ) if the results of applying B are a subset of the results of applying A for any database.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The two queries are said to be equivalent if the resulting sets are equal for any database.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This is important because in both GAV and LAV systems, a user poses conjunctive queries over a *virtual* schema represented by a set of views, or "materialized" conjunctive queries.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Integration seeks to rewrite the queries represented by the views to make their results equivalent or maximally contained by our user's query.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This corresponds to the problem of answering queries using views (AQUV).
[src:meltano/data-integration] In GAV systems, a system designer writes mediator code to define the query-rewriting.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Each element in the user's query corresponds to a substitution rule just as each element in the global schema corresponds to a query over the source.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Query processing simply expands the subgoals of the user's query according to the rule specified in the mediator and thus the resulting query is likely to be equivalent.
[src:meltano/data-integration] While the designer does the majority of the work beforehand, some GAV systems such as Tsimmis involve simplifying the mediator description process.
[src:meltano/data-integration] In LAV systems, queries undergo a more radical process of rewriting because no mediator exists to align the user's query with a simple expansion strategy.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The integration system must execute a search over the space of possible queries in order to find the best rewrite.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The resulting rewrite may not be an equivalent query but maximally contained, and the resulting tuples may be incomplete.
[src:meltano/data-integration] As of 2011 the GQR algorithm is the leading query rewriting algorithm for LAV data integration systems.
[src:meltano/data-integration] In general, the complexity of query rewriting is NP-complete.
[src:meltano/data-integration] If the space of rewrites is relatively small, this does not pose a problem — even for integration systems with hundreds of sources.
[src:meltano/data-integration] Large-scale questions in science, such as real world evidence, global warming, invasive species spread, and resource depletion, are increasingly requiring the collection of disparate data sets for meta-analysis.
[src:meltano/data-integration] This type of data integration is especially challenging for ecological and environmental data because metadata standards are not agreed upon and there are many different data types produced in these fields.
[src:meltano/data-integration] National Science Foundation initiatives such as Datanet are intended to make data integration easier for scientists by providing cyberinfrastructure and setting standards.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The Research Data Alliance, has more recently explored creating global data integration frameworks.
[src:meltano/data-integration] The OpenPHACTS project, funded through the European Union Innovative Medicines Initiative, built a drug discovery platform by linking datasets from providers such as European Bioinformatics Institute, Royal Society of Chemistry, UniProt, WikiPathways and DrugBank.
[src:meltano/dataops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:meltano/dataops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:meltano/dataops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:meltano/dataops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:meltano/dataops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:meltano/dataops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:meltano/dataops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:meltano/dataops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:meltano/dataops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:meltano/dataops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:meltano/dataops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:meltano/dataops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:meltano/dataops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:meltano/dataops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:meltano/dataops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:meltano/dataops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:meltano/dataops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:meltano/dataops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:meltano/dataops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:meltano/dataops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:meltano/dataops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:meltano/dataops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:meltano/dataops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:meltano/dataops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:meltano/dataops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:meltano/dataops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:meltano/dataops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:meltano/dataops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:meltano/dataops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:meltano/dataops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:meltano/dataops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:meltano/dataops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:meltano/dataops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:meltano/dataops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:meltano/dataops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:meltano/dataops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:meltano/dataops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:meltano/dataops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:meltano/dataops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:meltano/dataops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:meltano/dataops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:meltano/dataops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:meltano/dataops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:meltano/dataops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:meltano/dataops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:meltano/dataops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:meltano/dataops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:meltano/dataops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:meltano/dataops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:meltano/dataops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:meltano/dataops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:meltano/dataops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:meltano/dataops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:meltano/dataops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:meltano/dataops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:meltano/dataops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:meltano/dataops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:meltano/dataops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:meltano/dataops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:meltano/dataops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:meltano/dataops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:meltano/dataops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:meltano/dataops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:meltano/dataops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:meltano/dataops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:meltano/dataops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:meltano/dataops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:meltano/dataops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:meltano/dataops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:meltano/dataops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:meltano/dataops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:meltano/dataops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:meltano/dataops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:meltano/dataops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:meltano/dataops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:meltano/dataops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:meltano/dataops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:meltano/dataops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] The open-source, self-hosted foundation of Meltano.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] Own every part of your data infrastructure, on your own servers, free forever.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] Best for teams with DevOps capacity who want full control with zero vendor dependency.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] A fully managed hosted service built on top of Meltano Open.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] Pipelines, workspaces, secrets, and monitoring are all handled for you.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] No infrastructure to provision, patch, or maintain.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] Best for data teams who want to move fast without managing the plumbing.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] Browse the full Meltano reference documentation — CLI commands, settings, plugin definition syntax, and more.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] Explore the library of 600+ connectors and tools within the Meltano ecosystem.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] Build your own Meltano connector to move data from any source to any destination.
[src:meltano/docs-meltano-com] Explore many of the connectors built with the Meltano SDK in their home on GitHub: Meltano Labs.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:meltano/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] Meltano Hub is the single source of truth to find any Meltano plugins as well as Singer taps and targets.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] Users are also able to add more plugins to the Hub and have them immediately discoverable and usable within Meltano.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] The Hub is lovingly curated by Meltano and the wider Meltano community.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] If you're ready to build your ideal data platform and start running data workflows across multiple tools, start by following the Installation guide to have Meltano up and running in your device.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] See our Containerization guide for detailed usage instructions.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] Check out the "Getting Started" guide or find the full documentation at https://docs.meltano.com.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] Meltano is a truly open-source project, built for and by its community.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] We happily welcome and encourage your contributions.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] Start by browsing through our issue tracker to add your ideas to the roadmap.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] If you're still unsure on what to contribute at the moment, you can always check out the list of open issues labeled as "Accepting Merge Requests".
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] For more information on how to contribute to Meltano, refer to our contribution guidelines.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] We host weekly online events where you can engage with us directly.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] Check out more information in our Community page.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] If you have any questions, want sneak peeks of features or would just like to say hello and network, join our community of over +2,500 data professionals!
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] Please refer to the responsible disclosure policy on our website.
[src:meltano/main-readme-md] This code is distributed under the MIT license, see the LICENSE file.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open-source software development can bring in diverse perspectives beyond those of a single company.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] A 2024 estimate of the value of open-source software to firms is $8.8 trillion, as firms would need to spend 3.5 times the amount they currently do without the use of open source software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The Open Source Initiative's (OSI) definition is recognized by several governments internationally as the standard or *de facto* definition.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] OSI uses *The Open Source Definition* to determine whether it considers a software license open source.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The definition was based on the Debian Free Software Guidelines, written and adapted primarily by Bruce Perens.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Perens did not base his writing on the "four freedoms" from the Free Software Foundation (FSF), which were only widely available later.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Under Perens' definition, *open source* is a broad software license that makes source code available to the general public with relaxed or non-existent restrictions on the use and modification of the code.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] It is an explicit "feature" of open source that it puts very few restrictions on the use or distribution by any organization or user, in order to enable the rapid evolution of the software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Despite initially accepting it, Richard Stallman of the FSF now flatly opposes the term "Open Source" being applied to what they refer to as "free software".
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Although he agrees that the two terms describe "almost the same category of software", Stallman considers equating the terms incorrect and misleading.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Stallman also opposes the professed pragmatism of the Open Source Initiative, as he fears that the free software ideals of freedom and community are threatened by compromising on the FSF's idealistic standards for software freedom.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The FSF considers free software to be a subset of open-source software, and Richard Stallman explained that DRM software, for example, can be developed as open source, despite that it does not give its users freedom (it restricts them), and thus does not qualify as free software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In his 1997 essay *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*, open-source influential contributor Eric S.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Raymond suggests a model for developing OSS known as the *bazaar* model.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Raymond likens the development of software by traditional methodologies to building a cathedral, with careful isolated work by individuals or small groups.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] He suggests that all software should be developed using the bazaar style, with differing agendas and approaches.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In the traditional model of development, which he called the *cathedral* model, development takes place in a centralized way.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Roles include people dedicated to designing (the architects), people responsible for managing the project, and people responsible for implementation.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Traditional software engineering follows the cathedral model.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The bazaar model, however, is different.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In this model, roles are not clearly defined.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The process of Open source development begins with a requirements elicitation where developers consider if they should add new features or if a bug needs to be fixed in their project.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] This is established by communicating with the OSS community through avenues such as bug reporting and tracking or mailing lists and project pages.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Next, OSS developers select or are assigned to a task and identify a solution.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Because there are often many different possible routes for solutions in OSS, the best solution must be chosen with careful consideration and sometimes even peer feedback.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The developer then begins to develop and commit the code.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The code is then tested and reviewed by peers.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Developers can edit and evolve their code through feedback from continuous integration.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Once the leadership and community are satisfied with the whole project, it can be partially released and user instruction can be documented.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] If the project is ready to be released, it is frozen, with only serious bug fixes or security repairs occurring.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Finally, the project is fully released and only changed through minor bug fixes.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open source implementation of a standard can increase the adoption and long-term viability of that standard.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] It often fosters developer loyalty, as contributors feel a greater sense of participation and ownership in the development process and the end product.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Moreover, lower costs of marketing and logistical services are needed for OSS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] OSS can be a tool to promote a company's image, including its commercial products.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The OSS development approach has been known to some to help produce reliable, high quality software quickly and inexpensively.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open source development offers the potential to quicken innovation and create social value.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In France, for instance, a policy that incentivized government to favor free open-source software increased to nearly 600,000 OSS contributions per year, generating social value by increasing the quantity and quality of open-source software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] This policy also led to an estimated increase of up to 18% of tech startups and a 14% increase in the number of people employed in the IT sector.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] OSS can be highly reliable when it has thousands of independent programmers testing and fixing bugs of the software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open source is not dependent on the company or author that originally created it.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Even if the company fails, the code continues to exist and be developed by its users.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] OSS is flexible as modular systems allow programmers to build custom interfaces or add new abilities to it.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The mix of divergent perspectives, corporate objectives, and personal goals allows innovation.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Moreover, free software can be developed in accordance with purely technical requirements.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] It does not require thinking about commercial pressure that often degrades the quality of the software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Commercial pressures make traditional software developers pay more attention to customers' requirements than to security requirements, since such features are somewhat invisible to the customer.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In open-source software development, tools are used to support the development of the product and the development process itself.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Version control systems such as Centralized Version control system (CVCS) and the distributed version control system (DVCS) are examples of tools, often open source, that help manage the source code files and the changes to those files for a software project in order to foster collaboration.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] CVCS are centralized with a central repository while DVCS are decentralized and have a local repository for every user.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Concurrent Versions System (CVS) and later Subversion (SVN) are examples of CVCS, whereas Git is a DVCS and the most widely used version control software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The repositories are hosted and published on source-code-hosting facilities such as GitHub or Gitlab.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open-source projects use utilities such as issue trackers to organize open-source software development.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Commonly used bug trackers include Bugzilla and Redmine.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Tools such as mailing lists and IRC provide means of coordination and discussion of bugs among developers.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Project web pages, wiki pages, roadmap lists and newsgroups allow for the distribution of project information that focuses on end users.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The basic roles OSS participants can fall into multiple categories, beginning with leadership at the center of the project who have control over its execution.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Next are the core contributors with a great deal of experience and authority in the project who may guide the other contributors.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Non-core contributors have less experience and authority, but regularly contribute and are vital to the project's development.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] New contributors are the least experienced but with mentorship and guidance can become regular contributors.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Some possible ways of contributing to open-source software include such roles as programming, maintaining, user interface design and testing, web design, bug triage, accessibility design and testing, UX design, code testing, and security review and testing.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, there are several ways of contributing to OSS projects even without coding skills.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For example, some less technical ways of participating are documentation writing and editing, translation, project management, event organization and coordination, marketing, release management, community management, and public relations and outreach.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Funding is another way that individuals and organizations choose to contribute to open source projects.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Groups like Open Collective provide a means for individuals to contribute monthly to supporting their favorite projects.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Organizations like the Sovereign Tech Fund is able to contribute to millions to supporting the tools the German Government uses.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The National Science Foundation established a Pathways to Enable Open-Source Ecosystems (POSE) program to support open source innovation.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The adoption of open-source software by industry is increasing over time.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] OSS is popular in several industries such as telecommunications, aerospace, healthcare, and media & entertainment due to the benefits it provides.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Adoption of OSS is more likely in larger organizations and is dependent on the company's IT usage, operating efficiencies, and the productivity of employees.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Industries are likely to use OSS due to back-office functionality, sales support, research and development, software features, quick deployment, portability across platforms and avoidance of commercial license management.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Additionally, lower cost for hardware and ownership are also important benefits.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Organizations that contribute to the development and expansions of free and open-source software movements exist all over the world.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] These organizations are dedicated to goals such as teaching and spreading technology.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] As listed by a former vice president of the Open Source Initiative, some American organizations include the Free Software Foundation, Software Freedom Conservancy, the Open Source Initiative and Software in the Public Interest.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Within Europe some notable organizations are Free Software Foundation Europe, open-source projects EU (OSP) and OpenForum Europe (OFE).
[src:meltano/open-source-software] One Australian organization is Linux Australia while Asia has Open source Asia and FOSSAsia.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Free and open source software for Africa (FOSSFA) and OpenAfrica are African organizations and Central and South Asia has such organizations as FLISOL and GRUP de usuarios de software libre Peru.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Outside of these, many more organizations dedicated to the advancement of open-source software exist.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] FOSS products are generally licensed under two types of licenses: permissive licensing and copyleft licensing.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Both of these types of licenses are different than proprietary licensing in that they can allow more users access to the software and allow for the creation of derivative works as specified by the terms of the specific license, as each license has its own rules.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Permissive licenses allow recipients of the software to implement the author's copyright rights without having to use the same license for distribution.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Examples of this type of license include the BSD, MIT, and Apache licenses.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Copyleft licenses are different in that they require recipients to use the same license for at least some parts of the distribution of their works.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Strong copyleft licenses require all derivative works to use the same license while weak copyleft licenses require the use of the same license only under certain conditions.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Examples of this type of license include the GNU family of licenses, and the MPL and EPL licenses.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The similarities between these two categories of licensing include that they provide a broad grant of copyright rights, require that recipients preserve copyright notices, and that a copy of the license is provided to recipients with the code.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] One important legal precedent for open-source software was created in 2008, when the Jacobson v Katzer case enforced terms of the Artistic license, including attribution and identification of modifications.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The ruling of this case cemented enforcement under copyright law when the conditions of the license were not followed.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Because of the similarity of the Artistic license to other open-source software licenses, the ruling created a precedent that applied widely.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Examples of free-software license / open-source licenses include Apache licenses, BSD licenses, GNU General Public Licenses, GNU Lesser General Public License, MIT License, Eclipse Public License and Mozilla Public License.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Several gray areas exist within software regulation that have great impact on open-source software, such as if software is a good or service, what can be considered a modification, governance through contract vs license, ownership and right of use.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] While there have been developments on these issues, they often lead to even more questions.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The existence of these uncertainties in regulation has a negative impact on industries involved in technologies as a whole.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Within the legal history of software as a whole, there was much debate on whether to protect it as intellectual property under patent law, copyright law or establishing a unique regulation.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Ultimately, copyright law became the standard with computer programs being considered a form of literary work, with some tweaks of unique regulation.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Software is generally considered source code and object code, with both being protectable, though there is legal variety in this definition.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Some jurisdictions attempt to expand or reduce this conceptualization for their own purposes.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For example, The European Court of Justice defines a computer program as not including the functionality of a program, the programming language, or the format of data files.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] By limiting protections of the different aspects of software, the law favors an open-source approach to software use.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The US especially has an open approach to software, with most open-source licenses originating there.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, this has increased the focus on patent rights within these licenses, which has seen backlash from the OSS community, who prefer other forms of IP protection.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Another issue includes technological protection measures (TPM) and digital rights management (DRM) techniques which were internationally legally recognized and protected in the 1996 World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) Treaty.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open source software proponents disliked these technologies as they constrained end-users potentially beyond copyright law.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Europe responded to such complaints by putting TPM under legal controls, representing a victory for OSS supporters.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In open-source communities, instead of owning the software produced, the producer owns the development of the evolving software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In this way, the future of the software is open, making ownership or intellectual property difficult within OSS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Licensing and branding can prevent others from stealing it, preserving its status as a public good.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open source software can be considered a public good as it is available to everyone and does not decrease in value for others when downloaded by one person.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open source software is unique in that it becomes more valuable as it is used and contributed to, instead of diminishing the resource.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] This is explained by concepts such as investment in reputation and network effects.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The economic model of open-source software can be explained as developers contribute work to projects, creating public benefits.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Developers choose projects based on the perceived benefits or costs, such as improved reputation or value of the project.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The motivations of developers can come from many different places and reasons, but the important takeaway is that money is not the only or even most important incentivization.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Because economic theory mainly focuses on the consumption of scarce resources, the OSS dynamic can be hard to understand.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In OSS, producers become consumers by reaping the rewards of contributing to a project.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For example, a developer becomes well regarded by their peers for a successful contribution to an OSS project.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The social benefits and interactions of OSS are difficult to account for in economic models as well.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Furthermore, the innovation of technology creates constantly changing value discussions and outlooks, making economic model unable to predict social behavior.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Although OSS is theoretically challenging in economic models, it is explainable as a sustainable social activity that requires resources.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] These resources include time, money, technology and contributions.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Many developers have used technology funded by organizations such as universities and governments, though these same organizations benefit from the work done by OSS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] As OSS grows, hybrid systems containing OSS and proprietary systems are becoming more common.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Throughout the mid 2000s, more and more tech companies have begun to use OSS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For example, Dell's move of selling computers with Linux already installed.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Microsoft itself has launched a Linux-based operating system despite previous animosity with the OSS movement.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Despite these developments, these companies tend to only use OSS for certain purposes, leading to worries that OSS is being taken advantage of by corporations and not given anything in return.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, an issue to be considered is cybersecurity.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] While accidental vulnerabilities are possible, so are attacks by outside agents.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Because of these fears, governmental interest in contributing to the governance of software has become more prominent.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, these are the broad strokes of the issue, with each country having their own specific politicized interactions with open-source software and their goals for its implementation.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] These criteria include whether it comes from and is maintained by trusted sources, whether it will continue to be maintained, if there are dependencies on sub-components in the software, component security and integrity, and foreign governmental influence.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Another issue for governments in regard to open source is their investments in technologies such as operating systems, semiconductors, cloud, and artificial intelligence.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] These technologies all have implications for global cooperation, again opening up security issues and political consequences.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Many countries have to balance technological innovation with technological dependence in these partnerships.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For example, after China's open-source dependent company Huawei was prevented from using Google's Android system in 2019, they began to create their own alternative operating system: Harmony OS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Germany recently established a Sovereign Tech Fund, to help support the governance and maintenance of the software that they use.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In the early days of computing, particularly during the 1950s and 1960s, programmers and developers commonly shared software to learn from one another and advance the field.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Early systems such as Unix even provided users with access to their source code, allowing collaboration and modification.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, with the rise of the commercial software industry in the 1970s and 1980s, this culture of open sharing began to decline as proprietary models became dominant.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Despite this shift, academic and research institutions continued to promote collaborative software development practices.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In response, the open-source movement was born out of the work of skilled programmer enthusiasts, widely referred to as hackers or hacker culture.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] One of these enthusiasts, Richard Stallman, was a driving force behind the free software movement, which would later allow for the open-source movement.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In 1984, he resigned from MIT to create a free operating system, GNU, after the programmer culture in his lab was stifled by proprietary software preventing source code from being shared and improved upon.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] GNU was UNIX compatible, meaning that the programmer enthusiasts would still be familiar with how it worked.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, it quickly became apparent that there was some confusion with the label Stallman had chosen of free software, which he described as free as in free speech, not free beer, referring to the meaning of free as freedom rather than price.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] He later expanded this concept of freedom to the four essential freedoms.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Through GNU, open-source norms of incorporating others' source code, community bug fixes and suggestions of code for new features appeared.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In 1985, Stallman founded the Free Software Foundation (FSF) to promote changes in software and to help write GNU.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In order to prevent his work from being used in proprietary software, Stallman created the concept of copyleft, which allowed the use of his work by anyone, but under specific terms.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] To do this, he created the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL) in 1989, which was updated in 1991.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In 1991, GNU was combined with the Linux kernel written by Linus Torvalds, as a kernel was missing in GNU.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The operating system is now usually referred to as Linux.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] As free software developed, the Free Software Foundation began to look how to bring free software ideas and perceived benefits to the commercial software industry.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] It was concluded that FSF's social activism was not appealing to companies and they needed a way to rebrand the free software movement to emphasize the business potential of sharing and collaborating on software source code.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The term open source was suggested by Christine Peterson in 1998 at a meeting of supporters of free software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Many in the group felt the name free software was confusing to newcomers and holding back industry interest and they readily accepted the new designation of open source, creating the Open Source Initiative (OSI) and the OSI definition of what open source software is.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The Open Source Initiative's (OSI) definition is now recognized by several governments internationally as the standard or *de facto* definition.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The OSI definition differed from the free software definition in that it allows the inclusion of proprietary software and allows more liberties in its licensing.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Some, such as Stallman, agree more with the original concept of free software as a result because it takes a strong moral stance against proprietary software, though there is much overlap between the two movements in terms of the operation of the software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, while free and open-source software (FOSS) has historically played a role outside of mainstream private software development, companies as large as Microsoft have begun to develop official open source presences on the Internet.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] IBM, Oracle, and State Farm are just a few of the companies with a serious public stake in today's competitive open source market, marking a significant shift in the corporate philosophy concerning the development of FOSS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The future of the open source software community, and the free software community by extension, has become successful if not confused about what it stands for.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For example, Android and Ubuntu are examples milestones of success in the open source software rise to prominence from the sidelines of technological innovation as it existed in the early 2000s.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The use of OSS has become more common in business with 78% of companies reporting that they run all or part of their operations on FOSS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The popularity of OSS has risen to the point that Microsoft, a once detractor of OSS, has included its use in their systems.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, this success has raised concerns that will determine the future of OSS as the community must answer questions such as what OSS is, what should it be, and what should be done to protect it, if it even needs protecting.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] All in all, while the free and open source revolution has slowed to a perceived equilibrium in the market place, that does not mean it is over as many theoretical discussions must take place to determine its future.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open source software differs from proprietary software in that it is publicly available, the license requires no fees, modifications and distributions are allowed under license specifications.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] All of this works to prevent a monopoly on any OSS product, which is a goal of proprietary software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Proprietary software limits their customers' choices to either committing to using that software, upgrading it or switching to other software, forcing customers to have their software preferences impacted by their monetary cost.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The ideal case scenario for the proprietary software vendor would be a lock-in, where the customer does not or cannot switch software due to these costs and continues to buy products from that vendor.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Within proprietary software, bug fixes can only be provided by the vendor, moving platforms requires another purchase and the existence of the product relies on the vendor, who can discontinue it at any point.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Additionally, proprietary software does not provide its source code and cannot be altered by users.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For businesses, this can pose a security risk and source of frustration, as they cannot specialize the product to their needs, and there may be hidden threats or information leaks within the software that they cannot access or change.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Under OSI's definition, open source is a broad software license that makes source code available to the general public with relaxed or non-existent restrictions on the use and modification of the code.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] It is an explicit feature of open source that it puts very few restrictions on the use or distribution by any organization or user, in order to enable the rapid evolution of the software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Richard Stallman, leader of the Free software movement and member of the free software foundation opposes the term open source being applied to what they refer to as free software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Although he agrees that the two terms describe almost the same category of software, Stallman considers equating the terms incorrect and misleading.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] He believes that the main difference is that by choosing one term over the other lets others know about what one's goals are: development (open source) or a social stance (free software).
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Nevertheless, there is significant overlap between open source software and free software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The FSF considers free software to be a subset of open-source software, and Richard Stallman explained that DRM software, for example, can be developed as open source, despite how it restricts its users, and thus does not qualify as free software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The FSF said that the term open source fosters an ambiguity of a different kind such that it confuses the mere availability of the source with the freedom to use, modify, and redistribute it.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] On the other hand, the term free software was criticized for the ambiguity of the word free, which was seen as discouraging for business adoption, and for the historical ambiguous usage of the term.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Developers have used the alternative terms *Free and Open Source Software* (FOSS), or *Free/Libre and Open Source Software* (FLOSS), consequently, to describe open-source software that is also free software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Software can be distributed with source code, which is a code that is readable.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Software is source available when this source code is available to be seen.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However to be source available or FOSS, the source code does not need to be accessible to all, just the users of that software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] While all FOSS software is source available because this is a requirement made by the Open Source Definition, not all source available software is FOSS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For example, if the software does not meet other aspects of the Open Source Definition such as permitted modification or redistribution, even if the source code is available, the software is not FOSS.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] A recent trend within software companies is open-sourcing, or transitioning their previous proprietary software into open-source software through releasing it under an open-source license.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Examples of companies who have done this are Google, Microsoft and Apple.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Additionally, open-sourcing can refer to programming open-source software or installing open-source software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open-sourcing can be beneficial in multiple ways, such as attracting more external contributors who bring new perspectives and problem solving capabilities.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The downsides of open-sourcing include the work that has to be done to maintaining the new community, such as making the base code easily understandable, setting up communication channels for new developers and creating documentation to allow new developers to easily join.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, a review of several open-sourced projects found that although a newly open-sourced project attracts many newcomers, a great amount are likely to soon leave the project and their forks are also likely to not be impactful.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Other concepts that may share some similarities to open source are shareware, public domain software, freeware, and software viewers/readers that are freely available but do not provide source code.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, these differ from open source software in access to source code, licensing, copyright and fees.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Despite being able to collaborate internationally, open source software contributors were found to mostly be located in large clusters such as Silicon Valley that largely collaborate within themselves.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Possible reasons for this phenomenon may be that the OSS contributor demographic largely works in software, meaning that the OSS geographic location is closely related to that dispersion and collaborations could be encouraged through work and social networks.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Code acceptance can be impacted by status within these social network clusters, creating unfair predispositions in code acceptance based on location.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Barriers to international collaboration also include linguistic or cultural differences.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Furthermore, each country has been shown to have a higher acceptance rate for code from contributors within their country except India, indicating a bias for culturally similar collaborators.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In 2021, the countries with the highest open source software contributions included the United States, China, Germany, India, and the UK, in that order.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The countries with the highest OSS developers per capita from a study in 2021 include, in order, Iceland, Switzerland, Norway, Sweden, and Finland, while in 2008 the countries with top amount of estimated contributors in SourceForge were the United States, Germany, United Kingdom, Canada and France.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Though there have been several studies done on the distribution and contributions of OSS developers, this is still an open field that can be measured in several different ways.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For instance, Information and communication technology participation, population, wealth and proportion of access to the internet have been shown to be correlated with OSS contributions.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Although gender diversity has been found to enhance team productivity, women still face biases while contributing to open source software projects when their gender is identifiable.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In 2002, only 1.5% of international open-source software developers were women, while women made up 28% of tech industry roles, demonstrating their low representation in the software field.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, a more recent figure of female OSS participation internationally calculated across 2005 to 2021 is 9.8%, with most being recent contributors, indicating that female participation may be growing.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Contributors to OSS are motivated by belief in FOSS philosophy, personal interests, caring about the community, interest in projects and problem-solving, etc.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] In addition, users of a given software may also contribute as a way of improving tools they use, while others are drawn to the collaborative nature of open-source development environments.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Also, engagement with active projects allow contributors to stay current with industry practices and emerging trends.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The open source projects include the innovations and trends and they make it popular within the tech field.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Contributing to OSS can also increase a contributor's visibility and reputation within the community, as contributions are publicly accessible and can be reviewed by others.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] As a result, thousands of contributors daily contribute to the open source projects and help maintain it for the improvement of general public.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Even though programming was originally seen as a female profession, there remains a large gap in computing.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Social identity tends to be a large concern as women in the tech industry face insecurity about attracting unwanted male attention and harassment or being unfeminine in their technology knowledge, having a large impact on confidence.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Some male tech participants make clear that they believe women fitting in within the culture is impossible, furthering the insecurity for women and their place in the tech industry.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Additionally, even in a voluntary contribution environment like open source software, women tend to end up doing the less technical aspects of projects, such as manual testing or documentation despite women and men showing the same productivity in OSS contributions.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Explicit biases include longer feedback time, more scrutinization of code and lower acceptance rate of code.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Specifically in the open-source software community, women report that sexually offensive language is common and the women's identity as female is given more attention that as an OSS contributor.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Bias is hard to address due to the belief that gender should not matter, with most contributors feeling that women getting special treatment is unfair and success should be dependent on skill, preventing any changes to be more inclusive.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open source software projects are built and maintained by a network of programmers, who may often be volunteers, and are widely used in free as well as commercial products.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] While the term open source applied originally only to the source code of software, it is now being applied to many other areas such as open-source ecology, a movement to decentralize technologies so that any human can use them.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] However, it is often misapplied to other areas that have different and competing principles, which overlap only partially.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The same principles that underlie open-source software can be found in many other ventures, such as open source, open content, and open collaboration.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] This "culture" or ideology takes the view that the principles apply more generally to facilitate concurrent input of different agendas, approaches, and priorities, in contrast with more centralized models of development such as those typically used in commercial companies.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] More than 90 percent of companies use open-source software as a component of their proprietary software.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] The decision to use open-source software, or even engage with open-source projects to improve existing open-source software, is typically a pragmatic business decision.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] When proprietary software is in direct competition with an open-source alternative, research has found conflicting results on the effect of the competition on the proprietary product's price and quality.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] For decades, some companies have made servicing of an open-source software product for enterprise users their business model.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] These companies control an open-source software product, and instead of charging for licensing or use, charge for improvements, integration, and other servicing.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Software as a service (SaaS) products based on open-source components are increasingly common.
[src:meltano/open-source-software] Open-source software is preferred for scientific applications, because it increases transparency and aids in the validation and acceptance of scientific results.
